  "name": "Periplasmic and Membrane Stress (Cpx Response)",
  "notGates": 10,
  "notes": "The Cpx system is one of several envelope stress responses in E. coli (along with \u03c3E, Bae, Rcs). The CpxP-mediated feedback regulation is elegant: CpxP both inhibits the sensor (negative feedback) and is induced by the response (amplification), with substrate sequestration of CpxP providing the switching mechanism. DegP's temperature-dependent chaperone-to-protease switch is structurally remarkable. The Cpx response is important for virulence in pathogenic E. coli as it responds to host-induced stresses. This system exemplifies how bacteria monitor protein folding quality in different cellular compartments.",
  "organism": "E. coli",
  "relatedProcesses": [
    "ecoli_envelope_stress_response",
    "ecoli_heat_shock_response",
    "ecoli_protein_folding",
    "ecoli_two_component_signaling"
  ],
  "scientificAccuracy": "This flowchart is based on extensive genetic and biochemical studies of the Cpx system. All components (CpxA, CpxR, CpxP inhibitor), signaling mechanisms, and target genes have been well-characterized. The model represents a paradigm for bacterial envelope stress sensing and quality control in the periplasm.",
